          "title": "Hearing becomes seeing — testimony's epistemology",
          "body": "Verse 8 is the psalm's hermeneutical axis: 'As we have heard, so have we seen in the city of the Lord of hosts.' The congregation has received a tradition — what their fathers said God did — and they have now personally witnessed YHWH doing the same kind of thing again. The oral tradition and the present experience are congruent. This epistemological movement from hearing to seeing is the Bible's consistent pattern for the transmission of faith: Abraham heard the promise and saw the son; the Exodus generation heard the patriarchal narratives and saw the sea parted; the New Testament church heard the resurrection reports and saw the risen Lord (1 John 1:1-3). The congregation of Psalm 48 stands at the same juncture. And the Selah that closes verse 8 invites them — and us — to pause and register the weight of that alignment before proceeding."
