          "body": "The psalm's middle section (48:9-11) moves from exterior narrative to interior devotion. Inside the temple, the congregation meditates on YHWH's chesed — His steadfast covenant love (48:9). This is the word that explains the flight of the kings better than any military analysis can. YHWH routed the coalition not merely because He is powerful (so, too, are the gods of the nations, according to their own propaganda) but because He is covenantally committed to His people by a love that will not let them go. His name and His praise extend to the ends of the earth (48:10) — the God who dwells particularly in Zion is simultaneously the God whose fame belongs to every nation. His right hand is full of righteousness (48:10) — power and justice are not in tension but are co-present in everything He does. The daughters of Judah rejoice because of His judgments (48:11) — the same judgments that produce terror in the kings produce joy in the covenant community. The difference is not in what God did but in whose side you are on."
