          "body": "The psalm's closing movement (48:12-14) is startling in its concreteness. The congregation, having praised YHWH in the temple, is sent outside to walk the city's walls, count her towers, examine her ramparts, and tour her palaces — and then to go home and tell it to the next generation (48:12-13). The Hebrew verb saphar means both to count and to recount, to enumerate and to narrate. The physical act of inspecting the city's defenses is simultaneously the act of rehearsing YHWH's faithfulness — counting the towers is counting His mercies. The purpose clause is explicit: 'that you may tell it to the next generation' (48:13). The covenant community is not merely the recipient of YHWH's saving acts; it is the authorized transmitter of those acts into the future. The psalm closes with the confession that grounds this commission: 'For such is God, our God forever and ever; He will guide us until death' (48:14). The warrior King who routed the nations becomes the shepherd who guides His people to the very edge of death — and by implication, beyond it. The final word is not death but the God who accompanies us there."
